The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the pelvic region of the trunk. The walls of the pelvis are formed by bones and ligaments that are partly lined with muscles covered with fascia and parietal peritoneum.
A skeletal element that is part of a long bone and composed of cartilage tissue.
A lymph node located inferior to the ilium.
The mucosa of rumen is composed of a keratinised stratified squamous epithelium, is rich in mucopolysaccharides and is characterized by the presence of parakeratotis.
The retroauricular region is the area located behind the auricle of the outer ear.
The posterior aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.
The frontal aspect of the lower extremity that extends from the knee to the foot.

Mesenteric lymph node embedded in the ileocecal fold at both sides of the concavity of the cecum. It drains the terminal ileum.

Superior mediastinal lymph node located in the thoracic cavity between the lungs. It is bordered by the carina of the trachea, the lower lobe bronchus on the left and the intermediate bronchus on the right.
Supraclavicular lymph node located on the left side of a entire appendicular skeleton. The left supraclavicular lymph node drains the kidney, cervix, testis, and pancreas into the thoracic duct.
Supraclavicular lymph node located on the right side of a entire appendicular skeleton. The right supraclavicular lymph node drains the breast, lung and upper esophagus into the right lymphatic duct.

Lymph node that is the most proximal of the left supraclavicular lymph nodes. It receives afferent lymphatic drainage from the left head, neck, chest, abdomen, pelvis, and bilateral lower extremities, and drains into the jugulo-subclavian venous junction via the thoracic duct.
Lymph node located in the perigastric region.
The region of the body adjacent to the vertebral column.
The region of the body adjacent to the pericardium and heart.
A hyaline articular cartilage that covers the head of femur. Provides cushioning, softness and low friction for the hip joint.
The dorsal part of the iris. In urodeles (newts and salamanders) the dorsal iris is involved in lens regeneration in a process named Wolffian lens regeneration.

label.value: secretory coil of eccrine sweat gland

value.value: Tightly coiled tubule whose function is the production of sweat. The secretory tubule has three types of cells: clear, dark, and myoepithelial.

The labial gland is one of the minor salivary glands, located mainly under the mucosal epithelium of the upper and lower lip and within the orbicularis oris muscle fibers. The labial gland secrete mucous and serous substances to maintain oral health. In particular, the inferior labial gland not only promotes moisturization in the oral cavity but also secretes substances with antibacterial effects.
The region in the upper part of the back between the shoulder blades.
Microvessel located in the bone marrow, including arterioles and sinusoids.
A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a saphenous vein.
The region at each side of the face comprising the temple and the cheek.
This term is used to map the tissue from which the Muraoka cell line (CVCL_E042) originates.
An anatomical wall that surrounds the nasal cavity. The lateral walls of the nasal cavity are spiral shaped mucosal folds that overlie the turbinate and sinus ducts draining into the ostia.
A zone of skin that is part of the lobe tail.
A zone of skin on the front hindlimb zeugopod.
A zone of skin that is above the scapula in the upper back region.
A zone of skin part of some gonad.
